review_blob: Freshly canned rye IPA from Warped Wing. This is the first batch of canned beer released by WW. Canned on 7/14 - 8 days ago. Huge spicy nose followed by some sweet hops and pine. Beautiful golden color with no haziness at all. Medium body with moderate carbonation. Long finish with a good bite from the rye. A top notch IPA from these guys. Prost!

Pours with a heavier than expected beige head that leaves nice lacing. Deep copper color with aroma of sweet malt, raisins and substantial hops. Taste mirrors the aroma with a dash of alcohol presence.  Solid effort as expected by Alesmith.

From bottle.  Pours deep orange amber with very thin white head.
Grapefruit and citrus hops with some toasty malt aromas.  Citrus and fresh pine Very smooth and full mouthfeel.  Classic IIIPA.
From bottle.  Deep copper pour with a large off-white head. Candied apples,  caramel and banana, apple, plums, vanilla, dark fruits, and mild citrusy hops flavors.   Good carbonation.

From 750ml bottle.  Poured dark ruby/brown beer with a rich tan head with abundant lacing. Mild yeast  aromas.  Sweet sugary chocolate, raisin, flavors with no sign of alcohol.  Silky mouthfeel.  Classic Belgian....
Slightly hazy  deep straw color with nice white head with decent lacing.  Yeasty aromas with grassy hops and spice.  Citrusy with plenty of spicy herbal hops  Rich mouthfeel with good dryness.
On draft at Ale Fest Dayton 2009.  Pours black. Decent head with good retention and lacing.  Roasted malt and loads of hops on the taste combined with dark fruits like plums, raisins and cherries.
From 12oz bottle.  Pours light amber color with good lacing.  Aromas of balanced hops and malt with flavors of pine, citrus and banana bread.  Robust but smooth, hoppy flavors with long finish.
beer_name: Avery The Maharaja Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: From bottle.  Pours dark mahogany with off-white head. Aromas of malt, molasses and earthy hops. Alcoholic bite mixed with caramel, dark fruit and a dry hoppy finish. Medium-full body and carbonation.  Will improve even more with age.

2008 bottle.  Pours black with slight tan head that fades quickly.  
Strong coffee nose with plenty of alcohol.  Well balanced flavors of coffee, bitter chocolate, and bourbon. Low carbonation.  Classic brew......
From bomber.  Pours deep amber with a thick head   Nose is full of pine and citrus.  The citrusy hops come through strong. Somewhat thin, carbonated but well balanced.  Alcohol is well hidden.
Excellent from beginning to end.  Picked up for $10/4pk in KY.  Strong hop aroma.  Pours amber with decent head.  Long finish.  Excellent brew.
From bottle.  Strong fruit and hops aroma.  Full mouthfeel.  Great value - $6/bomber.  Definitely worth the money.
Poured from bottle.  Thanks to JeffE for this brewed.  Copper orange with virtually no head.  Sweet nose of toffee and malt.  Nice finish of fresh berries and brown sugar.
from bottle.    Pours copper with small off-white head. Minimal aroma of German malt/hops.  Strange metallic flavor and thin finish.  Acceptable session beer.  Nothing special.
From bottle.  Poured clear copper/orange with minimal head.  Lots of citrusy hops.  Not as hoppy on the palate as expected.  Good balance but not overly malty.  Decent finish.  Nice brew for $8.

Bottle. Pours a rich dark brown with decent tan head. Smells very sweet. HUGE chocolate flavor - actually too huge.  Nothing subtle about this beer.  One glass limit on this one - I appreciate the effort but other ST beers are better.

From bottle.  Pours classic hazy Belgian brown with generous head.  Aromas of sweet malt and mild spices.  Sweet dark fruit and malt and alcohol.  May need some time for the flavors to meld together.  Sweet finish.  For the price, it is a very good beer.  Will put a few away for a year or two and retry.

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours reddish/copper with thin white head. Aromas of caramel malt and citrusy hops.  Tastes mimic the nose but it is interrupted by a slight metallic taste..

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pour nearly black with dark latte colored head.  Aromas of dark chocolate and malt.  A fine blend of flavors coat your mouth - roasted nuts, espresso, and cocoa.  Long pleasing finish with the alcohol just peeking through a little.  High quality at a great price.  Good job Garrett.

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours cloudy honey/brown with a thick eggshell head. Aromas of citrus   hopd and malt.  The 80IBUs show in the taste with force.  Decent finish.  As others have said - the color is not the best - so close your eyes and enjoy the taste if you get a chance.

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours hazy gold color with decent white head. So far so good - but then ...... Strange metallic flavors overpower the taste.  Not good.  Avoid.

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours dark borwn/black with tan head.  Simple malt aromas mix with coffee.  Tastes include chocolate, espresso  and a hoppy finish.  Decent but not a standout.

From bottle/kettle.  Pours cloudy golden brown with no head.  Aromas are intense featuring tree nuts, caramel, brown sugar and dried dark fruit. Flavors mirror the nose with maple and vanilla joining the parade.  Very smooth considering the alcohol content.  Glad to try it with forking over $100+.

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.   Pours nearly black with brown head.  Aromas of coffee, malt and smoke.  Flavors of coffee and chocolate dominate the taste.  Not as full bodies as expected.  Nice long finish.  Good effort.

From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours black full brown foamy head.  Aromas of coffee, hops and chocolate.  Sweet complex flavors include smoke, vanilla, coffee and licorice.  Outstanding effort.

From 750ml bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours a hazy amber with decent off-white head. Spicy aromas mixed with caramel and nuts.  Taste mimics the nose.  Alcohol is clearly present but not overbearing.  Sweet finish.

From bottle, Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours a clear pale yellow with robust white head.   Artificially sweet aromas mixed with bread/yeast.  Thin mouthfeel with mild hops and not much else.
From bottle.  Part of  Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours deep red/brown with light tan head.  Aroma of hops, coffee and nuts.  Taste follows the nose with some spice and earthy textures.

From bottle.  Part of  Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours dark brown with short tan head. Aromas are primarily coffe and sweet malt.  Medium mouthfeel with more coffee and chocolate flavors.   Easy drinking but not an elite beer.
beer_name: Left Hand Wake Up Dead Imperial Stout

review_blob: From bottle.  Part of January Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours amber with decent white head. Aroma was primarily citrusy hops. Short finish after simple hop flavors.

Draft @ Falling Rock, Danver.  Pours clear yellow color with slight short lived white head.  Nose is full of citrus hops, spinces and yeast.  Flavors are restrained with hops, fresh bread and spices.  A decent beer but it didnt live up to my hopes.

Draft @ GABF.  Pours pitch black with thin dark tan head. Aroma of sweet dark fruits and faint coffee.  Very complex flavors with molasses, coffee, soy and chocolate.  One of the best Imp Stouts Ive had.
Draft @ GABF.  Pours pitch black with generous tan head. Aroma of roasted malt, alcohol and dark fruits. Taste was filled with licorice, malt, coffee and molasses. Huge mouthfeel with long finish.
Draft @ GABF.  Poured pitch black with ample brown head. Aromas of roasted malt, anise and chocolate.  Taste was filled with coffee, caramel, chocolate and brown sugar.   Long finish.  Great effort.

From bottle.  Pours clear copper with generous off-white head. The aroma includes spicy hops, caramel malt and faint citrus. Tastes medium bodied with roasted malts and generous hops.  Decent beer but not worth the $8 tariff.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: From bottle.  Pours amber red with slight off white head.  Mild hop aroma with citrus flavors.  Strange metallic finish that hurts the overall rating.

From bomber.  Pours clear amber red with loose white head.  Strong blend of piney hops and malt.  Rich full mouthfeel with pine, caramel, subtle spice and more hops.  Well the $7 pricetag.  The 9% alcohol will catchup with you though......

From bottle.  Pours amber with slight tan head.  Aroma is of sweet malt and spice.  
Decent mouthfeel with a good spice blend, caramel and malt.  Alcohol is very well hidden. I was surprised to see it was 7.5%.  Decent winter warmer.
From bottle.  Pours brown with decent dark tan head. Aromas of chocolate and malt.  Flavors include light chocolate and toffee. Smooth but thin body. Pretty bottle but not worth the $13-15 price tag.

From bottle.  Part of November Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours copper with decent white head.  Spices, sugar and earth comprise the taste with a funky finish. Decent mouthfeel - better than the Matilda.

From bottle.  Part of November Dayton Beer Tasting event.  Pours hazy orange/amber with small head.  Aroma of yeast, oranges and spice.  Flavors match the aroma with the addition of malt and dark fruit.  Decent attempt at a Belgian.
From bottle.  Pours hazy amber with decent head and lacing. Huge hop aroma.  Good balance of hops and malt flavors.    This is my first Simcoe-only brew.  Excellent effort.

Draft @ Falling Rock, Denver.  Pours copper with a small tight head with great lacing.  Aroma is of sweet malt, grapefruit and strong hops. Flavor is filled with toffee and hop flavors.  A little too much alcohol is present.

From bottle.  Nectar of the gods!  Pours dark brown color with short tan head with long lasting lacing. Aromas of malts, dried dark fruit. Tastes is sweet dark fruit, nuts, caramel with a long tangy finish.  Alcohol is compeltely hidden.  Excellent as usual.
From bottle.  Pours dark black with small tan head.  Aromas of dark fruit and chocolate.  Very muddled appearance due to the chocolate.  Smooth finish with decent length.
From bottle.  Pours clear yellow color with loose white head. Sour citrus and yeast aromas  Mildly spicy with ginger, herbs and toast flavors.
From bottle.  Poured black with chocolate and caramel aromas. Full bodied with heavy dark chocolate, currants and spice.  Nice long smooth finish considering the high alcohol content.

From bottle.  Cellared for1 year.
Poured red/brown with large loose head. Aromas of caramel, yeast and bananas.  Sweet blend of bread, dark fruit, caramel and vanilla.  Cellaring definitely helped smooth it out and add complexity.
From bottle.  Poured a dark amber with thin  head.  Typical Irish red.  Decent choice vs. Killians, etc.
